  <exercise label="Library__UMN__calculusStewartET__s_12_1_10" xml:id="ex-9-1-WW-point-coordinate-planes2">
    <!--<title>Point to coordinate planes</title>-->
     <webwork source="Library/UMN/calculusStewartET/s_12_1_10.pg"/>
  </exercise>


<exercise>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this problem, we will look at how the set of points that satisfies an equation, <m>x=2</m>, will have a different description whether we think about our points being in one dimension (on a number line), in two dimensions (in the Cartesian plane), or in three dimensions (in space). 
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Describe the set of points that satisfies <m>x=2</m> if you consider the space to be <m>\mathbb{R}</m> (the number line). Your description should include a sentence or two detailing the set and a plot of the graph of <m>x=2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The set of points that satisfies <m>x=2</m> on the number line is simply the point two units to the right of the origin on the number line. Graphically, this looks like:
      </p>
      <image width="60%">
        <sageplot>
          plot1=point((2,0),size=30,ticks=[[-2,-1,0,1,2],[]],axes_labels=["$x$",""],xmin=-2.5,xmax=2.5,ymin=-0.05,ymax=0.05)
          plot1+=text("$x=2$",(2.1,0.01),color="black",fontsize=20)
          plot1              
        </sageplot>
      </image>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Describe the set of points that satisfies <m>x=2</m> if you consider the space to be <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> (the cartesian plane). Your description should include a sentence or two detailing the set and a plot of the graph of <m>x=2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The set of points that satisfies <m>x=2</m> in the plane is the vertical line two units to the right of the vertical axis. Graphically, this looks like:
      </p>
      <image width="60%">
        <sageplot>
          var('t')
          plot9=parametric_plot((2,t),(t,-4,4),color="blue",gridlines=True,aspect_ratio=1,axes=true,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"])
          plot9+=text("$x=2$",(2.8,0.2),color="blue",fontsize=20)
          plot9+=point((0,0),color="black",size=0,xmin=-4,xmax=4,ymin=-4,ymax=4)
          plot9             
        </sageplot>
      </image>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Describe the set of points that satisfies <m>x=2</m> if you consider the space to be <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> (3D space). Your description should include a sentence or two detailing the set and a plot of the graph of <m>x=2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The set of points that satisfies <m>x=2</m> in space is the plane parallel to and two units in front of the <m>yz</m>-plane . Graphically, this looks like:
      </p>
      <image width="60%">
        <interactive platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            var('t,s')
            from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
            plot9=axes(3,1,color="black",frame=False,aspect_ratio=1)+text3d("x",(3.5,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,3.5,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,3.5),fontsize=30)
            plot9+=parametric_plot((2,t,s),(t,-3,3),(s,-3,3),color="blue",opacity=0.4,plot_points=5,mesh=True,aspect_ratio=1,frame=False)
            plot9+=text3d("x=2",(2.8,1.2,1.2),color="blue",fontsize=20)
            show(plot9,camera_position=[3.4443,12.355,4.2937],viewpoint=[[-0.0414,-0.5852,-0.8099],173.44])             
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </image>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="yneqfx">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this exercise, we want to graphically identify when a given plot can be expressed as:
      <ul>
        <li><m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>, but <m>x</m> cannot be written as a function of <m>y</m></li>
        <li><m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m>, but <m>y</m> cannot be written as a function of <m>x</m></li>
        <li><m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> and <li><m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m></li></li>
        <li>neither <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> nor <li><m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m></li></li>
      </ul> 
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each graph in <xref ref="coord2d-four-graphs"/>, state which of the four options above applies to whether the graph can be expressed with each coordinate being a function of the other or not. If the graph cannot be expressed with <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>, write a sentence about what property you used to determine this. If the graph cannot be expressed with <m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m>, write a sentence about what property you used to determine this.
      </p>
        <figure xml:id="coord2d-four-graphs">
        <caption>Four plots to determine if the graphs depict <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m></caption>
        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="0% 0%">
          <sidebyside>
            <figure>
              <image width="45%" label="img-coord2d-PA6">
                <description><p>A two-dimensional plot of a parabola opening in the positive vertical direction. </p></description>
                <sageplot>
                  var('x')
                  plot6=plot(x^2,(x,-4,4),color="black",axes=true,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],gridlines=True,xmin=-4,xmax=4,ymin=-4,ymax=4,aspect_ratio=1)
                  plot6   
                </sageplot>
              </image>
            </figure>
            <figure>
              <image width="45%" label="img-coord2d-PA7">
                <description><p>A two-dimensional plot of a parabola opening in the positive horizontal direction.</p></description>
                <sageplot>
                  var('t')
                  plot7=parametric_plot((t^2,t),(t,-4,4),color="black",axes=true,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],gridlines=True,aspect_ratio=1)
                  plot7+=point((0,0),color="black",size=0,xmin=-4,xmax=4,ymin=-4,ymax=4)
                  plot7
                </sageplot>
              </image>  
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
          <sidebyside>
            <figure>
              <image width="45%" label="img-coord2d-PA8">
                <description><p>A two-dimensional plot of a line with slope <m>1</m> and <m>y</m>-intercept <m>1</m>.</p></description>
                <sageplot>
                  var('t')
                  plot8=parametric_plot((t,t+1),(t,-4,4),color="black",axes=true,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],gridlines=True,xmin=-4,xmax=4,ymin=-4,ymax=4,aspect_ratio=1)
                  plot8
                </sageplot>
              </image>
            </figure>
            <figure>
              <image width="45%" label="img-coord2d-PA9">
                <description><p>A two-dimensional plot of a vertical line with <m>x</m>-intercept <m>2</m>.</p></description>
                <sageplot>
                  var('t')
                  plot9=parametric_plot((2,t),(t,-4,4),color="black",gridlines=True,aspect_ratio=1,axes=true,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"])
                  plot9+=point((0,0),color="black",size=0,xmin=-4,xmax=4,ymin=-4,ymax=4)
                  plot9
                </sageplot>
              </image>             
            </figure>       
          </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
      </figure>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The graph in part a can be expressed with <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> but not <m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m>. The graph in part b can be expressed with <m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m> but not <m>y</m> as a function of <m>s</m>. The graph in part c can be expressed with <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> and <m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m>. The graph in part d can be expressed with <m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m> but not <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="yneqfx2">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this exercise, we want to algebraically identify when the graph of a given equation can be expressed as:
      <ul>
        <li><m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>, but <m>x</m> cannot be written as a function of <m>y</m></li>
        <li><m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m>, but <m>y</m> cannot be written as a function of <m>x</m></li>
        <li><m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> and <li><m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m></li></li>
        <li>neither <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> nor <li><m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m></li></li>
      </ul> 
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each equation below, state which of the four options above applies to whether the graph can be expressed with each coordinate being a function of the other or not. 
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <md>3x-2y=10 </md>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <md>3x^2+2y^2=10 </md>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <md>3y=10x^2-10 </md>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <md>y=5 </md>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <md>x=2 </md>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>  
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
         <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Both coordinates expressible as a function of the other
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Neither coordinate expressible as a function of the other
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Both coordinates expressible as a function of the other
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y</m> is a function of <m>x</m> but not the other way around.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x</m> is a function of <m>y</m> but not the other way around.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="Ez-9-1-1">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Find the equation of each of the following geometric objects.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The plane parallel to the <m>xy</m>-plane that passes through the point <m>(-4,5,-12)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>z = -12</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>z = -12</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The plane parallel to the <m>yz</m>-plane that passes through the point <m>(7, -2, -3)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x = 7</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x = 7</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>  
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The sphere centered at the point <m>(2,1,3)</m> and has the point <m>(-1,0,-1)</m> on its surface.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>(x-2)^2 + (y-1)^2 + (z-3)^2 = 26</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>(x-2)^2 + (y-1)^2 + (z-3)^2 = 26</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>       
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The sphere whose diameter has endpoints <m>(-3,1,-5)</m> and <m>(7,9,-1)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>(x-2)^2 + (y-5)^2 + (z+3)^2 = 45</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>(x-2)^2 + (y-5)^2 + (z+3)^2 = 45</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>     
  </exercise>
  
